node.text:
#NoShaping! 😃 I work with some pretty strong bread flour, and generally need a high hydration (88-90% 💦) to keep my dough nice and extensible - if I happen to reduce the water (~84% 💦), then the result is a more stiff dough that requires maybe 1-2 coil folds throughout bulk! In this particular case, I tipped my dough out from the dish onto the counter to shape, and thought to myself that my usual shaping method would over-tighten the dough. So that's when I thought about my friend Pekka...!

Pekka @panedepain shared this #noshaping technique awhile back - he demonstrates how a normal coil fold, performed later in the bulk, can serve as the actual shaping... Then, after a short rest, he simply flips the dough straight from the dish right into the banneton! 😱😍👌 See his featured highlight on this subject!

In this video here I'm showing sort of an adaptation of this - and it can be used whenever I feel my dough is overly taut at the end of bulk (when it's either too low hydration, or I've done the final coil too late, or it's simply overly proofy). So if you ever do a coil on the later side and notice your dough seems sort of tight and you can't really get a great shaping out of it, try this super minimalist method!! 😁💛🌾

Dough is 30% semola flour, 70% @centralmilling Electra Light, 84% hydration. 2 coil folds throughout bulk (~75°F, 6.5 hrs). Pressed wood pulp banneton by @flourside_ 🙏 Followed Basic Method as seen in the link in my Insta bio! ❤️

node.text:
A back to basics loaf! 🌾🥰 For me, baking = joy. I can't seem to get enough of it.... The mixing of the various flour blends, the smell of the doughy mix, the way the dough develops and how it feels as it stretches out. Deciding what next inclusions to try out and observing how they affect the quality of the dough, taking notes. Watching the dough as it grows - becoming supple and smooth and puffy, full of millions of little air bubbles - it's alive!!! ❤️ That final moment too, pulling the lid off in the bake to see the bloom 🔥... Smelling that fresh warm bread smell every morning. The final slicing and slathering with butter or dipped in oil - oh man, I am totally hooked 😂 Happy baking everyone - and please read to the end for a very important message 🙏🤗

For this loaf, I stuck completely to my Basic Method (see the link in my bio and my full YouTube tutorial or pre-recorded workshop). Autolysed (2 hrs) 275g flour blend (30g fresh milled @meadowlark_organics wheat berries + 30g white @kamutbrand Kamut + 215g @bobsredmill artisan bread flour) + 235g water.
Hang mixed in the levain (55g), then the salt (6g).
3 coil folds throughout bulk. Shaped at ~75% total dough rise (6.5 hrs at ~75°F).
Overnight cold rest at 38°F. Baked next morning using @challengerbreadware pan as usual!

At the end here: I wanted to say a massive and very heartfelt THANK YOU 🙏🙏🙏 to everyone who sent in uplifting words and/or who ordered from my Shopify store this last few days. I cannot explain how much this means to me. This little business has sure taken me on an emotional roller coaster this last year and I am so happy to see product bring fulfilled at our warehouse and knowing jars and kits and starter are going out to bakers all around the world! Watching it all come together: It's unbelievable, really. Crazy amazing - I thank you so very much for your support, your enthusiasm, your generosity 🥰❤️🥰❤️🥰 Thank you, and happy baking!! I hope you all love your jars and starter as much as I love them!!

node.text:
Sprouted Kamut sourdough bread! 🌾🤤 It's been awhile since I've baked a delicious sprouted loaf and I'm glad I prepped extra sprouts in my freezer! Please see my previous post for how to prepare your own sprouts at home - it's so easy!! And swipe over on this post to see videos of how I grind the berries and also how I fold them into the dough 👍

After mixing my autolyse (I used a basic white blend of 30% white Kamut flour + 70% @centralmilling Electra Light here at ~86% hydration), I took my frozen berries from the fridge and let them thaw. Right before adding to my dough, I used my mini blender to process the sprouts into a mash pulp (I added 15g extra water to the sprouts to allow them to blend more smoothly)... Then folded them into my dough (60g berries total) right after I added the salt. Totally wonderful dough!!

Bulk went a little faster as expected, as addition of sprouts to a dough gives more sugars and enzymes which contributes to a more efficient ferment 😍 About 5.5 hours at ~75°F is all it took! Just enough coils to build strength along the way 👌

Hope you try this one out, guys! Super simple but great flavor that I'm sure you'll love. Try with sprouted rye or buckwheat or spelt too -- really whatever you have on hand 🥰 Happy baking!

node.text:
Sprouting your whole grain berries adds incredible flavor and nutrients to your sourdough breads - it's my favorite way to incorporate whole grains!! The process takes 2-3 days usually and very minimal effort -- and leaves you with these little sprouts that taste grassy and sugary. These are Kamut berries, but I've sprouted all sorts of grains: spring wheat, spelt, rye, and buckwheat! All delicious and add delicious depth of flavor 🤤

Once sprouted, I'll portion 60-75g aliquots into individual baggies and freeze them until I'm ready to use them. I grind them up and fold into my dough while they're still wet and fresh like a mash (see following post for a recipe); others dry their sprouts out and mill them and add as flour to their bread recipes. I've done this before too and it's also delicious 😁❤️

Adding sprouts adds sugars and enzymes to your bread dough - so be sure to watch your fermentation. All this activity can lead to over fermenting, and a gummy interior. So just, be careful! It's well worth it if you try it out - I promise!

Day 1: in the morning or before bed, soak a cup of berries in two cups warm water. Let sit 8-12 hours to activate.
Day 2: rinse the berries and spread out on a sprouting tray (I put my favorite on my Baking Supplies page which you can find in the link in my bio at the bottom of the list of links there) or place in a colander or simply a bowl. Cover lightly and place somewhere warm. Wait 12 hours and rinse again.
Day 3: you may be done if you see little tails of the sprout growing out the tip of each berry! If you'd like the sprouts to grow a bit more, do another rinse and 12 hour rest. Some berries take longer to sprout than others!

I package into little food safe snack baggies and store in the freezer. See next post for more info on how I prefer to use these berries! 🥰😋🌾

This is a solid bread that I will definitely be making again: 25% bolted wheat, with molasses and extra virgin olive oil 😋 Brought two of these larger sized loaves to Michigan this week for a short vacation with friends (used 400g flour blend for each autolyse). The little bit of oil helped preserve the softness of the crumb overnight, and the molasses added just a touch of sweetness and depth of flavor. And of course I'm always in love with this @meadowlarkorganics bolted wheat 🌾💖 Cut some extra thick slices to dip in a Shakshouka recipe I tried out 🤤

I'm returning home today and can report the baker's percentages of molasses and oil then! ☺️ Happy baking everyone!!

Update: followed my basic method like you can find in the link in my bio. 
110g bolted wheat + 290g @centralmilling Electra Light + 340g water + 10g molasses + 5g extra virgin olive oil all combined by hand, then allowed to rest in autolyse for 2 hours.
Mixed in 80g just peaked levain, then 30 min later 10g salt.
Total bulk lasted 6.5 hours at 76°F.
5 coil folds separated evenly throughout bulk.
Shaped, final proofed at 38°F 8 hours.
Baked as usual using @challengerbreadware pan!

See the link in my bio for more tips including my full online pre-recorded classes on starter care and how to make a loaf of open crumb sourdough bread! 🥰❤️

node.text:
On a roll here with these soft pretzels that I'm bringing to New Buffalo, Michigan for a short vacation with a few friends!! 😄 Soft pretzel dough doesn't have to be tricky to make at all! Such an easy dough - mix all ingredients from the start using a mixer. Bulk the dough until it doubles in volume (I bulked overnight). Divided and rounded, then rolled out the dough in two stages like in the video. Popped into the fridge for 1-4 hours! I like this flexible step 😃 Then dip in cold lye solution, salt and score and bake! 🥨😋 Originally started with the recipe by @maurizio and have adapted it to fit my schedule, my flour, and based on my husband's feedback. Hope you try it out!!

Ingredients to mix: 
1000g flour (a blend of @centralmilling 500g strong Electra Light and 500g Artisan Baker's Craft)
1 tsp diastatic malt
20g salt
50g very ripe and active levain
560g water (room temp)
40g barley malt syrup (I buy mine online - see my baking supplies page at the bottom of the link in my bio)
77g soft room temp butter

Knead with dough hook 15 min, then pop in a bowl and bulk overnight until doubled (10 hours at 68°F/20°C).

Divide (14x120g each), pre-shape, rest 20 min.
Final shape, refrigerate uncovered 2 hours (1-4 hours).

Dip 14 sec in a lye solution (the sodium hydroxide lye I purchase is also on my Baking Page!). 1000g COLD water + 40g lye. Be careful, use gloves, maybe goggles too 👩‍🔬 Use a baked baking soda recipe if you don't use lye (see recipes online).

Pretzel salt, score, push apart scored seam slightly, then bake in a 425°F preheated convection on for 8 min.
Rotate trays, then bake another 8 min at 425°F conventional.

Cool and enjoy!! 🥨🥰🤩 Warning: they'll ruin you for other pretzels!!

The very day my new bag of @meadowlark_organics bolted wheat (which I use in my sandwich breads) arrived, I got an email from my friend Dan Ayo (Fresh Loaf Forum). He tells me I should try skipping the bulk stage in my next sandwich bread prep and simply allow all the dough rise time directly in the tins! 😃 This seemed as good a time as any to try it out...

I figured I would need to do a bit more dough development at the beginning, so I would use my KitchenAid mixer to develop the dough for 5-10 min at a time, with 30 min rests in between each ingredient incorporation. So so simple and easy, and with such great results!! The recipe notes are below - and I can't believe how sweet and mild this loaf turned out (no sour flavor). Super soft and tender too! 

You can prep this dough in the morning and proof during the day (bake at night), or you can prep at night before bed and proof overnight (bake in morning) 🌾

Recipe makes two 13x4x4" pan loaves...
If working with two 9x5" tins: multiply each ingredient by 0.87.
If working with two 8x4.5" tins: multiply each ingredient by 0.74.

Prep levain overnight: 1:6:6 (20g active starter + 120g flour + 120g water). Rest at ~75-78°F until peaked.
In the morning, in your mixer bowl, knead together: 250g levain + 1000g flour (I use a mix of 500g all purpose by @kingarthurbaking + 250g bolted wheat by @meadowlark_organics + 250g @centralmilling ABC+; feel free to use your favorite flour blend!) + 600g warm 80-85°F water. Knead 10 min with dough hook then rest 45 min.
Add in 22g salt + 100g brown sugar + 50g milk powder. Knead 10 min, rest 30 min.
Slowly, pat at a time, knead in fully softened butter (170g) until fully incorporated ~10 min. Rest 30 min.
One final kneading round (5 min with dough hook), then divide the dough into 2 and roll up into logs and place into parchment-lined tins.
**Proof rise until dough reaches just to the rim of the pan, ~10 hrs at ~76°F**
Preheat oven to 425°F, 30 mins. Bake breads for 30 min at 400°F, then another 30 min at 350°F.
Remove from tins and place on a cooling rack, covered with a towel overnight (helps soften the crust further)! 🧡😁

node.text:
Carrot puree makes for a lovely lightly sweet and tender bake! I used a bunch of steamed carrots, pureed with a bit of water and then used this to hydrate my flour in the autolyse step. Whenever I use carrot I need to add a great deal of water as, over the course of bulk, my dough tightens up. This time the dough felt completely beautiful and extensible since I added enough water... Dough handled and developed well, giving me a soft, lacy crumb and shiny, blistery crust in the end 😍 See full recipe notes below, and hope you try it out! 🥕😋

Prepped carrots by steaming for 12 minutes, then pureeing with a mini blender. Total of 100g steamed carrots + 75g water.
Used puree plus another 130g water to hydrate 275g flour (I used a very a blend of strong bread flour here that could hold up to the carrot). 50/50 mix of @bobsredmill Artisan BF and @centralmilling Electra Light. If using different flour, hold back water until you can see how much water it can take!! 💦
Autolysed 2 hours.
Hand mixed in the 55g levain and then 30 min later, 6.5g salt.
Bulked for 7.5 hours at ~75-76°F, with gentle coil folds as needed (1 full coil + 3 half coils, separated about evenly throughout the bulk). Dough was light and puffed by the the I went to shape, approx doubled in volume.
Shaped, overnight proofed in fridge, baked in @challengerbreadware pan.

Please see the link in my Instagram bio for more detail on every part of my method I like to use, including my comprehensive start-to-finish Workshop now posted -- for 20% off the class price use Promo JULYPROMO101!

Gonna spend the rest of the day celebrating my now EIGHT year old's birthday!! 🎉🤗 Oh my goodness, how fast they grow!!! 🥲

Beautiful lacy crumb - my favorite 😍😋 20% sifted whole wheat flour and 80% strong bread flour at ~88% hydration. I prepared the levain and cold, refrigerated autolyse (with salt added for added stability) overnight and woke first thing to start my bulk. My dough was shaped and into the fridge for final proof by early afternoon. Another overnight in the fridge and baked the next day - wonderful depth of flavor, a bit more tanginess overall plus such a silky light texture... And holy cow those blisters! ❤️

Overnight levain built 1:10:10 (3g active starter + 30g flour + 30g water) and kept around 76°F. Peaked about 10 hours after feed.

Overnight autolyse prepared by mixing 275g flour blend (60g sifted @heckers_ceresota_flour whole wheat + 215g @bobsredmill Artisan Bread Flour) + 240g water + 6.5g salt.

Following morning, brought dough out on the counter and let warm up for an hour before mixing in the levain and initiating bulk. Bulk was a little longer, I believe because the dough was still a little cool from the beginning and because I'm using my all-white bread flour starter... About 8 hours total at 75-76°F. Final proof at 38°F 18 hours. Baked in @challengerbreadware pan as usual with an ice cube to boost steam.

Please see the link in my Instagram bio at the top of my page for more tips on every part of the process, including my new comprehensive workshop (use promo code JULYPROMO101 to take 20% off the listed price!) 🥰
